# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: starlette-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:starlette-framework/applications] Starlette includes an application class `Starlette` that nicely ties together all of its other functionality.
[src:starlette-framework/applications] You can store arbitrary extra state on the application instance, using the generic `app.state` attribute.
[src:starlette-framework/applications] Where a `request` is available (i.e. endpoints and middleware), the app is available on `request.app`.
[src:starlette-framework/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] The **Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface** (**ASGI**) is a calling convention for web servers to forward requests to asynchronous-capable Python frameworks, and applications.
[src:starlette-framework/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] It is built as a successor to the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI).
[src:starlette-framework/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] Where WSGI provided a standard for synchronous Python applications, ASGI provides one for both asynchronous and synchronous applications, with a WSGI backwards-compatibility implementation and multiple servers and application frameworks.
[src:starlette-framework/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] ASGI is also designed to be a superset of WSGI, and there's a defined way of translating between the two, allowing WSGI applications to be run inside ASGI servers through a translation wrapper (provided in the asgiref library).
[src:starlette-framework/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] A threadpool can be used to run the synchronous WSGI applications away from the async event loop.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] Middleware makes it easier for software developers to implement communication and input/output, so they can focus on the specific purpose of their application.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] It gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] The term is most commonly used for software that enables communication and management of data in distributed applications.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] An IETF workshop in 2000 defined middleware as "those services found above the transport (i.e. over TCP/IP) layer set of services but below the application environment" (i.e. below application-level APIs).
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] In this more specific sense *middleware* can be described as the hyphen ("-") in *client-server*, or the *-to-* in *peer-to-peer*.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] Middleware includes web servers, application servers, content management systems, and similar tools that support application development and delivery.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] Database access services are often characterised as middleware.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] Some of them are language specific implementations and support heterogeneous features and other related communication features.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] Examples of database-oriented middleware include ODBC, JDBC, and transaction processing monitors.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] Distributed computing system middleware can loosely be divided into two categories—those that provide human-time services (such as web request servicing) and those that perform in machine-time.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] This latter middleware is somewhat standardized through the Service Availability Forum and is commonly used in complex, embedded systems within the telecom, defence, and aerospace industries.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] Many categories of middleware have been defined, based on the field in which it is used or the application module it serves.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] The term *middleware* is used in other contexts as well.
[src:starlette-framework/middleware] *Middleware* is sometimes used in a similar sense to a software driver, an abstraction layer that hides detail about hardware devices or other software from an application.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:starlette-framework/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] Starlette includes a `Request` class that gives you a nicer interface onto the incoming request, rather than accessing the ASGI scope and receive channel directly.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] Requests present a mapping interface, so you can use them in the same way as a `scope`.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] For instance: `request['path']` will return the ASGI path.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] If you don't need to access the request body you can instantiate a request without providing an argument to `receive`.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] The request method is accessed as `request.method`.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] The request URL is accessed as `request.url`.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] The property is a string-like object that exposes all the components that can be parsed out of the URL.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] For example: `request.url.path`, `request.url.port`, `request.url.scheme`.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] Headers are exposed as an immutable, case-insensitive, multi-dict.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] Query parameters are exposed as an immutable multi-dict.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] Router path parameters are exposed as a dictionary interface.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] The client's remote address is exposed as a named two-tuple `request.client` (or `None`).
[src:starlette-framework/requests] Cookies are exposed as a regular dictionary interface.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] Cookies are ignored in case of an invalid cookie.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] If you access `.stream()` then the byte chunks are provided without storing the entire body to memory.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] Any subsequent calls to `.body()`, `.form()`, or `.json()` will raise an error.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] In some cases such as long-polling, or streaming responses you might need to determine if the client has dropped the connection.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] You can determine this state with `disconnected = await request.is_disconnected()`.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] Request files are normally sent as multipart form data (`multipart/form-data`).
[src:starlette-framework/requests] These limits are for security reasons, allowing an unlimited number of fields or files could lead to a denial of service attack by consuming a lot of CPU and memory parsing too many empty fields.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] When you call `async with request.form() as form` you receive a `starlette.datastructures.FormData` which is an immutable multidict, containing both file uploads and text input.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] File upload items are represented as instances of `starlette.datastructures.UploadFile`.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] `UploadFile` has the following `async` methods.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] They all call the corresponding file methods underneath (using the internal `SpooledTemporaryFile`).
[src:starlette-framework/requests] As all these methods are `async` methods, you need to "await" them.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] As settled in RFC-7578: 4.2, form-data content part that contains file assumed to have `name` and `filename` fields in `Content-Disposition` header: `Content-Disposition: form-data; name="user"; filename="somefile"`.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] Though `filename` field is optional according to RFC-7578, it helps Starlette to differentiate which data should be treated as file.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] If `filename` field was supplied, `UploadFile` object will be created to access underlying file, otherwise form-data part will be parsed and available as a raw string.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] The originating Starlette application can be accessed via `request.app`.
[src:starlette-framework/requests] If you want to store additional information on the request you can do so using `request.state`.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] Starlette has a simple but capable request routing system.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] A routing table is defined as a list of routes, and passed when instantiating the application.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] Paths can use URI templating style to capture path components.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] `Route('/users/{username}', user)` By default this will capture characters up to the end of the path or the next `/`.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] You can use convertors to modify what is captured.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] If you need a different converter that is not defined, you can create your own.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] Path parameters are made available in the request, as the `request.path_params` dictionary.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] By default function endpoints will only accept `GET` requests, unless specified.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] In large applications you might find that you want to break out parts of the routing table, based on a common path prefix.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] This style allows you to define different subsets of the routing table in different parts of your project.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] You can also use mounting to include sub-applications within your Starlette application.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] You'll often want to be able to generate the URL for a particular route, such as in cases where you need to return a redirect response.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] URL lookups can include path parameters...
[src:starlette-framework/routing] If a `Mount` includes a `name`, then submounts should use a `{prefix}:{name}` style for reverse URL lookups.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] Mounted applications may include a `path=...` parameter.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] For cases where there is no `request` instance, you can make reverse lookups against the application, although these will only return the URL path.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] If you want to use different routes for the same path based on the `Host` header.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] Note that port is removed from the `Host` header when matching.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] For example, `Host (host='example.org:3600', ...)` will be processed even if the `Host` header contains or does not contain a port other than `3600` (`example.org:5600`, `example.org`).
[src:starlette-framework/routing] Therefore, you can specify the port if you need it for use in `url_for`.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] Incoming paths are matched against each `Route` in order.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] In cases where more that one route could match an incoming path, you should take care to ensure that more specific routes are listed before general cases.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] If you're working at a low-level you might want to use a plain `Router` instance, rather that creating a `Starlette` application.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] This gives you a lightweight ASGI application that just provides the application routing, without wrapping it up in any middleware.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] When working with WebSocket endpoints, you should use `WebSocketRoute` instead of the usual `Route`.
[src:starlette-framework/routing] Path parameters, and reverse URL lookups for `WebSocketRoute` work the same as HTTP `Route`, which can be found in the HTTP Route section above.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:starlette-framework/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] WebSocket is distinct from HTTP used to serve most webpages.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Although they are different, RFC 6455 states that WebSocket "is designed to work over HTTP ports 443 and 80 as well as to support HTTP proxies and intermediaries", making the WebSocket protocol compatible with HTTP.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] To achieve compatibility, the WebSocket handshake uses the HTTP Upgrade header to change from the HTTP protocol to the WebSocket protocol.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The WebSocket protocol enables full-duplex interaction between a web browser (or other client application) and a web server with lower overhead than half-duplex alternatives such as HTTP polling, facilitating real-time data transfer from and to the server.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] This is achieved by providing a standardized way for the server to send content to the client without being first requested by the client, and allowing messages to be exchanged while keeping the connection open.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] In this way, a two-way ongoing conversation can take place between the client and the server.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The communications are usually done over TCP port number 443 (or 80 in the case of unsecured connections), which is beneficial for environments that block non-web Internet connections using a firewall.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Additionally, WebSocket enables streams of messages on top of TCP.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] TCP alone deals with streams of bytes with no inherent concept of a message.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Similar two-way browser–server communications have been achieved in non-standardized ways using stopgap technologies such as Comet or Adobe Flash Player.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Most browsers support the protocol, including Google Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Internet Explorer, Safari and Opera.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The WebSocket protocol specification defines `ws` (WebSocket) and `wss` (WebSocket Secure) as two new uniform resource identifier (URI) schemes that are used for unencrypted and encrypted connections respectively.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Apart from the scheme name and fragment (i.e.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] `#` is not supported), the rest of the URI components are defined to use URI generic syntax.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] WebSocket was first referenced as TCPConnection in the HTML5 specification, as a placeholder for a TCP-based socket API.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] In June 2008, a series of discussions were led by Michael Carter that resulted in the first version of the protocol known as WebSocket.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Before WebSocket, port 80 full-duplex communication was attainable using Comet channels; however, Comet implementation is nontrivial, and due to the TCP handshake and HTTP header overhead, it is inefficient for small messages.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The WebSocket protocol aims to solve these problems without compromising the security assumptions of the web.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The name "WebSocket" was coined by Ian Hickson and Michael Carter shortly thereafter through collaboration on the #whatwg IRC chat room, and subsequently authored for inclusion in the HTML5 specification by Ian Hickson.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] In December 2009, Google Chrome 4 was the first browser to ship full support for the standard, with WebSocket enabled by default.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Development of the WebSocket protocol was subsequently moved from the W3C and WHATWG group to the IETF in February 2010, and authored for two revisions under Ian Hickson.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] After the protocol was shipped and enabled by default in multiple browsers, the RFC 6455 was finalized under Ian Fette in December 2011.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] RFC 7692 introduced compression extension to WebSocket using the DEFLATE algorithm on a per-message basis.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] A web application (e.g. web browser) may use the `WebSocket` interface to maintain bidirectional communications with a WebSocket server.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] **Frame-based message** exchange: data, ping and pong messages.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] **Closing handshake**: close message (request then echoed in response).
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The client sends an **HTTP request** (**method** **GET**, **version ≥ 1.1**) and the server returns an **HTTP response** with **status code 101** (*Switching Protocols*) on success.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] HTTP and WebSocket clients can connect to a server using the same port because the opening handshake uses HTTP.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Sending additional HTTP headers (that are not in the table below) is allowed.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] After the *Switching Protocols* HTTP response, the opening handshake is complete, the HTTP protocol stops being used, and communication switches to a binary frame-based protocol.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The following Python code generates a random `Sec-WebSocket-Key`.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The following Python code calculates `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` using `Sec-WebSocket-Key` from the example request above.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] `Sec-WebSocket-Key` and `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` are intended to prevent a caching proxy from re-sending a previous WebSocket conversation, and does not provide any authentication, privacy, or integrity.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Though some servers accept a short `Sec-WebSocket-Key`, many modern servers will reject the request with error "invalid Sec-WebSocket-Key header".
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] After the opening handshake, the client and server can, at any time, send **data messages** (text or binary) and **control messages** (*Close*, *Ping*, *Pong*) to each other.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] A message is composed of **one frame if unfragmented** or **at least two frames if fragmented**.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] A **client must mask** all frames sent to the server.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] A **server must not mask** any frames sent to the client.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Frame masking applies **XOR between the payload and the masking key**.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The following pseudocode describes the algorithm used to both mask and unmask a frame.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The `permessage-deflate` extension allows data messages to be compressed using the DEFLATE algorithm.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] For example, during the opening handshake, the client and server may use the following header to enable the extension.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The `RSV1` field of the first frame of a data message must be set to indicate the payload data is compressed.
