[src:starlette-framework/websocket] A secure version of the WebSocket protocol is implemented in Firefox 6, Safari 6, Google Chrome 14, Opera 12.10 and Internet Explorer 10.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] A detailed protocol test suite report lists the conformance of those browsers to specific protocol aspects.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] An older, less secure version of the protocol was implemented in Opera 11 and Safari 5, as well as the mobile version of Safari in iOS 4.2.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The BlackBerry Browser in OS7 implements WebSockets.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Because of vulnerabilities, it was disabled in Firefox 4 and 5, and Opera 11.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Using browser developer tools, developers can inspect the WebSocket handshake as well as the WebSocket frames.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] ASP.NET Core have support for WebSockets using the `app.UseWebSockets();` middleware.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Unlike regular cross-domain HTTP requests, WebSocket requests are not restricted by the same-origin policy.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] It is better to use tokens or similar protection mechanisms to authenticate the WebSocket connection when sensitive (private) data is being transferred over the WebSocket.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] A live example of vulnerability was seen in 2020 in the form of Cable Haunt.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] WebSocket protocol client implementations try to detect whether the user agent is configured to use a proxy when connecting to destination host and port, and if it is, uses HTTP CONNECT method to set up a persistent tunnel.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] The WebSocket protocol is unaware of proxy servers and firewalls.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Some proxy servers are transparent and work fine with WebSocket; others will prevent WebSocket from working correctly, causing the connection to fail.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] In some cases, additional proxy-server configuration may be required, and certain proxy servers may need to be upgraded to support WebSocket.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] If unencrypted WebSocket traffic flows through an explicit or a transparent proxy server without WebSockets support, the connection will likely fail.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] If an encrypted WebSocket connection is used, then the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS) in the WebSocket Secure connection ensures that an `HTTP CONNECT` command is issued when the browser is configured to use an explicit proxy server.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] This sets up a tunnel, which provides low-level end-to-end TCP communication through the HTTP proxy, between the WebSocket Secure client and the WebSocket server.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] In the case of transparent proxy servers, the browser is unaware of the proxy server, so no `HTTP CONNECT` is sent.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] However, since the wire traffic is encrypted, intermediate transparent proxy servers may simply allow the encrypted traffic through, so there is a much better chance that the WebSocket connection will succeed if WebSocket Secure is used.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] Using encryption is not free of resource cost, but often provides the highest success rate, since it would be travelling through a secure tunnel.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] A mid-2010 draft (version hixie-76) broke compatibility with reverse proxies and gateways by including eight bytes of key data after the headers, but not advertising that data in a `Content-Length: 8` header.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] This data was not forwarded by all intermediates, which could lead to protocol failure.
[src:starlette-framework/websocket] More recent drafts (e.g., hybi-09) put the key data in a `Sec-WebSocket-Key` header, solving this problem.
